   "title": "Module 1 · Prisms & Cylinders",
   "html": "<ul><li>Cube: $V=a^3$; SA $=6a^2$.</li><li>Cuboid: $V=lbh$; SA $=2(lb+bh+lh)$.</li><li>Cylinder: $V=\\pi r^2 h$; total SA $=2\\pi r(r+h)$.</li></ul>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Find the volume of a cylinder with $r=7$ cm, $h=10$ cm (take $\\pi=22/7$).",
     "a": "$V = \\tfrac{22}{7}\\times 49\\times 10 = 1540\\ \\text{cm}^3$."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "title": "Module 2 · Cones, Spheres, Pyramids",
   "html": "<ul><li>Cone: $V=\\tfrac{1}{3}\\pi r^2 h$; slant $l=\\sqrt{r^2+h^2}$; curved SA $=\\pi r l$.</li><li>Sphere: $V=\\tfrac{4}{3}\\pi r^3$; SA $=4\\pi r^2$.</li><li>Pyramid: $V=\\tfrac{1}{3}(\\text{base area})\\times h$.</li></ul>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Volume of a sphere with $r=3$ cm (take $\\pi=22/7$).",
     "a": "$V = \\tfrac{4}{3}\\times \\tfrac{22}{7}\\times 27 = \\tfrac{2376}{21} \\approx 113.14\\ \\text{cm}^3$."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "title": "Module 3 · Frustums",
   "html": "<p>A frustum is what remains after cutting the top off a cone (or pyramid) with a plane parallel to the base.</p>$$V_{\\text{frustum}} = \\tfrac{1}{3}\\pi h(R^2 + Rr + r^2)$$",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "State the frustum volume formula.",
     "a": "$V=\\tfrac{1}{3}\\pi h(R^2 + Rr + r^2)$ where $R$, $r$ are the radii of the two circular faces and $h$ is the perpendicular distance between them."
    }
   ]
  }
 ],
